00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.780
we were Wednesday and launch
back into mass parabolas, which

00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:07.170
are ways of looking at nuclear
stability in relative numbers

00:01:07.170 --> 00:01:09.370
and even or oddness of nuclei.

00:01:09.370 --> 00:01:11.100
So you saw last
time we intuitively

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:13.860
derived the semi-empirical
mass formula

00:01:13.860 --> 00:01:19.620
as a sum of volume,
surface, coulomb, asymmetry,

00:01:19.620 --> 00:01:23.850
and pairing, or whether things
are even-even or odd-even terms

00:01:23.850 --> 00:01:28.140
with the coefficients in
MeV gleaned from data,

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:31.770
and the forms of the-- and the
exponents right here gleaned

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:33.420
from intuition.

00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:34.950
Here we assume that
the nucleus can

00:01:34.950 --> 00:01:38.010
be thought of like a big drop
of liquid with some charged

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:39.400
particles in it.

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:41.430
And so the droplet
should become more stable

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:44.820
the more nuclei there are-- or
the more nucleons there are.

00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:46.740
But then you have
some more outside

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:48.840
on the surface that aren't
bonded to the others.

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:52.388
All of the protons are repelling
each other over linear length

00:01:52.388 --> 00:01:54.305
scales, because the
radius of this liquid drop

00:01:54.305 --> 00:01:56.560
would scale like A to the 1/3.

00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:59.130
There's an asymmetry term,
which means if the neutrons

00:01:59.130 --> 00:02:01.470
and protons are out
of balance, there's

00:02:01.470 --> 00:02:04.548
going to be some
less binding energy.

00:02:04.548 --> 00:02:06.090
And then there's
this extra part that

00:02:06.090 --> 00:02:09.780
tells you whether the nuclei
are even-even or odd-odd.

00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:11.820
And this works pretty well.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:14.580
If you remember, we looked
at theory versus experiment

00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:17.910
where all the red points here
are theoretical predictions,

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:20.730
and all the black points are
experimental predictions.

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:22.560
And for the most part,
they look spot-on.

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:25.650
It generates the classic
binding energy per nucleon

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:27.540
curve that you see
in the textbook

00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:30.660
and can predict from the
semi-empirical mass formula.

00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:33.570
Zooming in and correcting
for, let's say,

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:35.740
just getting absolute
values of errors,

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:38.880
you can see that, except
for the very small nuclei

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:41.160
and a few peaks,
which we explained

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:44.130
by looking even closer,
the formula, well,

00:02:44.130 --> 00:02:48.085
it predicts nuclear stability
quite well on average.

00:02:48.085 --> 00:02:49.710
Again, this line
right here, if there's

00:02:49.710 --> 00:02:51.790
a dot that lies
on this blue line,

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:54.660
it means that theory
and experiment agree.

00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:58.860
And a deviation by a few MeV
here and there, not too bad.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:01.620
But we started also looking
at different nuclear stability

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:05.610
trends, and we noticed that
for odd mass number nuclei,

00:03:05.610 --> 00:03:10.500
there's usually only one or
sometimes none stable isotopes

00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:13.830
per Z, whereas for even ones,
there's quite a few more.

00:03:13.830 --> 00:03:15.540
And we're going to
be now linking up

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:18.600
the stability of nuclei
versus what mode of decay

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:22.590
they will take in order to find
a more stable configuration.

00:03:22.590 --> 00:03:25.650
We looked quickly at the number
of stable nuclei with even

00:03:25.650 --> 00:03:29.370
and odd Z and noted that
these places right here where

00:03:29.370 --> 00:03:33.300
there are no stable nuclei
correspond to technetium

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:34.740
and promethium.

00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:37.000
There's no periodic table
on the back of this wall,

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:38.765
but behind my back
on the other wall,

00:03:38.765 --> 00:03:40.140
there's that
periodic table where

00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:42.510
you can see the two
elements that are fairly

00:03:42.510 --> 00:03:44.340
light with no stable isotopes.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:46.290
That's what those correspond to.

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:49.950
And the peaks correspond to
what we call magic numbers

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:52.650
or numbers of
protons or neutrons

00:03:52.650 --> 00:03:54.630
where all available
states at some energy

00:03:54.630 --> 00:03:56.040
are pretty much filled.

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:59.050
And this goes for both
protons and neutrons.

00:03:59.050 --> 00:04:03.180
So something with a magic number
for both n, number of neutrons,

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:04.740
and Z, number of
protons, is going

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:06.625
to be exceptionally stable.

00:04:06.625 --> 00:04:08.250
And we'll see how
that's used as a tool

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:11.370
to synthesize the super heavy
elements that we believe

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:14.070
should exist.

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:16.470
And finally we got into
these mass parabolas.

00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:18.750
I found this to be a
particularly difficult concept

00:04:18.750 --> 00:04:20.640
to just get mathematically.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:23.700
If you remember, we wrote out
the semi-empirical mass formula

00:04:23.700 --> 00:04:26.880
and said if you take the
derivative with respect to Z,

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:31.550
as we did it, you would get the
most stable z for a given A.

00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:34.350
And we started graphing
for a equals 93

00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:36.782
where niobium is stable.

00:04:36.782 --> 00:04:39.240
That was just the one I had on
the brain from some failures

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:41.460
in lab earlier this week.

00:04:41.460 --> 00:04:44.830
We started plotting
where those nuclei--

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:48.150
what is it-- the relative
masses are for a fixed A. So

00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:49.830
let's regenerate
that one right now,

00:04:49.830 --> 00:04:52.290
because we were a little fast
at the end of last lecture.

00:04:52.290 --> 00:04:56.132
Then I want to generate
one for a equals 40.

00:04:56.132 --> 00:04:57.840
And you'll see something
kind of curious.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:00.090
I'm going to leave
this up here for a sec.

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:03.150
If you notice, for
odd A nuclei, there's

00:05:03.150 --> 00:05:06.895
only one parabola, whereas
for even A, there are two.

00:05:06.895 --> 00:05:08.520
Why that is, we're
going to see when we

00:05:08.520 --> 00:05:10.090
look at the table of nuclides.

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:12.450
But notice this
nucleus right here

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:16.230
can decay by either positron
emission or beta emission

00:05:16.230 --> 00:05:17.520
to get to a more stable form.

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:18.895
And there are many
real examples,

00:05:18.895 --> 00:05:22.270
and I'm going to show
you how to find them.

00:05:22.270 --> 00:05:26.160
So let's start off by going
back to the table of nuclides,

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:29.330
finding niobium-93.

00:05:29.330 --> 00:05:32.520
Just go up one more chunk.

00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:34.650
And there we are.

00:05:34.650 --> 00:05:38.280
Niobium-93 is a stable isotope.

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:40.030
And if you want to see
where it came from,

00:05:40.030 --> 00:05:43.080
you can scroll down a little
bit and see its possible parent

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:45.010
nuclides right here.

00:05:45.010 --> 00:05:47.670
So let's say that niobium--

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:49.560
we'll draw it right there--

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:50.190
is stable.

00:05:50.190 --> 00:05:52.850
We'll put it at the
bottom of this parabola.

00:05:52.850 --> 00:05:57.560
And let's work down in Z.
So we'll move to zirconium.

00:05:57.560 --> 00:06:02.240
Zirconium-93 ostensibly has
a very similar atomic mass.

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:07.040
But if you remember that 93 AMU
is a rather poor approximation

00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:11.180
for the actual mass of all
nuclei with A equals 93.

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:14.330
In fact, if you look very
closely at the atomic masses,

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:18.660
zirconium-93 is 92.90.

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:21.060
Niobium-93, well,
it looks like we

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:23.310
have to go all the way
to another digit there.

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:26.560
92.906.

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:31.680
You have to go to, like,
even more digits 92.906375,

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:34.290
92.906475.

00:06:34.290 --> 00:06:36.270
So we go down in Z,
and we've actually

00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:40.170
gone up in mass by looks like
the sixth or seventh digit

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:41.470
in AMU.

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:44.430
If we go up in mass, we
go down in binding energy.

00:06:44.430 --> 00:06:47.010
That tells us that there's
something that's less stable.

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:49.650
And if you notice, we went
down by a very small--

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:52.950
or we went up by a very
small amount of mass.

00:06:52.950 --> 00:06:56.820
Notice also that its beta decay
energy is really, really small,

00:06:56.820 --> 00:06:59.070
91 kiloelectron volts.

00:06:59.070 --> 00:07:03.670
So why don't we put
zirconium just above?

00:07:03.670 --> 00:07:05.390
And we note that that
decay will happen

00:07:05.390 --> 00:07:09.860
by beta, where the
beta, let's say

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:14.280
if we have an isotope with
mass number A, protons Z,

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:17.030
and let's just call it
symbol question mark.

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:20.810
In beta decay, we
have the same A.

00:07:20.810 --> 00:07:22.820
We'll have a different
Z. We're going

00:07:22.820 --> 00:07:24.740
to have to give these symbols.

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:28.880
Let's call this parent, and
we'll call that daughter.

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:32.517
Plus a beta, plus an
electron antineutrino.

00:07:32.517 --> 00:07:34.850
And what has to happen to
that Z in order for everything

00:07:34.850 --> 00:07:36.980
to be conserved?

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:39.750
It's the same reaction
that we've got here for--

00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:41.640
I'm sorry-- for zirconium.

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:47.100
So you'd have to have one fewer
proton to release one electron.

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:49.320
And so that becomes
same A but different Z.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:51.120
And this is the
beta decay reaction.

00:07:56.670 --> 00:07:58.560
Let's go back a little farther.

00:07:58.560 --> 00:08:00.645
We'll look at the possible
parent nuclide for--

00:08:00.645 --> 00:08:01.770
did anyone have a question?

00:08:01.770 --> 00:08:06.560
AUDIENCE: Don't you need
one more proton [INAUDIBLE]??

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:07.600
PROFESSOR: Let's see.

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:09.580
Which direction are
we going in Z here?

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:14.252
That goes to yttrium.

00:08:14.252 --> 00:08:16.298
It actually looks
like it's going down.

00:08:16.298 --> 00:08:17.340
Oh, yeah, for beta decay.

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:21.030
I'm thinking-- I have
the reaction backwards.

00:08:21.030 --> 00:08:22.870
Sorry.

00:08:22.870 --> 00:08:25.380
I need one more
proton to account

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:26.630
for the extra negative charge.

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:27.750
You're right.

00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:28.290
OK.

00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:30.290
Yep, I was thinking
backwards, because we're now

00:08:30.290 --> 00:08:32.799
climbing up the decay
chain in reverse order.

00:08:32.799 --> 00:08:35.980
So this could have come
from yttrium-93 with a much

00:08:35.980 --> 00:08:37.480
higher energy of three MeV.

00:08:37.480 --> 00:08:40.809
So let's put yttrium right here.

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:46.330
That gives a beta decay.

00:08:46.330 --> 00:08:52.750
And we'll just go one more
back to strontium-93 Has

00:08:52.750 --> 00:08:56.507
an even higher
beta decay energy.

00:08:56.507 --> 00:08:57.590
So let's put that up here.

00:09:00.710 --> 00:09:03.120
And let's take a look
at its mass real quick.

00:09:03.120 --> 00:09:08.270
The mass of
strontium-93, 92.914 AMU.

00:09:08.270 --> 00:09:13.290
If we go back to
niobium-93, now it's

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:16.410
noticeably different to,
like, four significant digits

00:09:16.410 --> 00:09:17.178
instead of six.

00:09:17.178 --> 00:09:21.540
92.914 versus 92.906.

00:09:21.540 --> 00:09:24.780
And so that shows you that
a tiny bit of mass and AMU

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:26.850
corresponds to a pretty
significant change

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:30.450
in binding energy by that
same conversion factor

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:33.630
that we've been
using everywhere.

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:45.910
931.49 AMU per big
MeV per C squared.

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:47.570
Let's see.

00:09:47.570 --> 00:09:48.170
Yeah.

00:09:48.170 --> 00:09:48.670
OK.

00:09:50.930 --> 00:09:53.690
So let's go now in the other
direction, in the positron

00:09:53.690 --> 00:09:54.900
direction.

00:09:54.900 --> 00:10:00.410
Niobium can also be
made by electron capture

00:10:00.410 --> 00:10:01.820
from molybdenum.

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:05.860
So let's put
molybdenum right here.

00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:08.113
Let's say that around half an--

00:10:08.113 --> 00:10:09.030
what did we have here?

00:10:09.030 --> 00:10:10.030
It was like half an MeV.

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:15.697
Like that.

00:10:15.697 --> 00:10:16.280
And let's see.

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:19.670
Molybdenum-93 could have
been made by electron capture

00:10:19.670 --> 00:10:24.905
from technetium-93 with
an energy of 3.201 MeV,

00:10:24.905 --> 00:10:25.655
even more extreme.

00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:34.080
We'll go back one more, because
there's a trend that I want

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:35.850
you guys to be able to see.

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:37.830
And this could have come
from electron capture

00:10:37.830 --> 00:10:40.620
from ruthenium.

00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:42.570
I think I may have said
rubidium last time,

00:10:42.570 --> 00:10:44.350
but Ru is ruthenium-93.

00:10:47.460 --> 00:10:52.740
And that 6.3 MeV,
something like that.

00:10:52.740 --> 00:10:55.400
And this is where
we got to yesterday.

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:57.950
Now I'd like us to take a
closer look at the decay

00:10:57.950 --> 00:11:01.640
diagrams, which tells us what
possible decay reactions can

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:04.580
happen in each of
these reactions.

00:11:04.580 --> 00:11:06.080
Since we're right
here on the chart,

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:10.520
let's take a look at ruthenium
turning into technetium by what

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:11.840
it says, electron capture.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:14.900
So note that on the table, you
can click on electron capture,

00:11:14.900 --> 00:11:17.870
and if it's highlighted, then
the decay diagrams are known.

00:11:17.870 --> 00:11:20.150
It's not known
for every isotope,

00:11:20.150 --> 00:11:23.020
but for a lot of the ones
you'll be dealing with, it is.

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:26.990
And you get something I
have to zoom out for--

00:11:26.990 --> 00:11:29.600
a lot, a lot of
different decays.

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:32.150
What I want you to look at is
this one here on the bottom

00:11:32.150 --> 00:11:35.400
that I'll zoom in to.

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:37.740
That should be a
little more visible.

00:11:37.740 --> 00:11:42.100
So notice that if you want to
go down the entire 6.4-something

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:51.180
MeV, it usually proceeds by
B-plus or positron decay,

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:52.980
by either method.

00:11:52.980 --> 00:11:56.160
And as you go up the chain, as
these energy differences get

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:59.130
smaller, look what
happens to the probability

00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:00.900
of getting positron decay.

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:03.060
It shrinks lower
and lower and lower.

00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:05.220
So there's a trend that
the larger the decay

00:12:05.220 --> 00:12:08.310
energy for this type of
reaction, the more likely

00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:10.710
you're going to
get positron decay.

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:13.650
And in fact, where we left
off last time is in order

00:12:13.650 --> 00:12:18.120
to get positron decay, the
Q value of the reaction

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:23.730
has to be at least
1.022 MeV, better known

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:29.940
as at least two times the
rest mass of the electron,

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:32.580
because in this case, to
conserve charge and energy,

00:12:32.580 --> 00:12:34.890
you shoot out a
positron, and you also

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:36.960
have to eject an
electron in order

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:40.160
to conserve all the
charge going on here.

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:42.940
So there you have it.

00:12:42.940 --> 00:12:47.670
Now let's look at the lower
energy decay of technetium

00:12:47.670 --> 00:12:49.230
to molybdenum,
which had something

00:12:49.230 --> 00:12:52.620
like 3 MeV associated with it.

00:12:52.620 --> 00:12:57.790
So we'll click on technetium,
and its energy is 3.2 MeV.

00:12:57.790 --> 00:13:00.820
Let's take a look at
