00:33:20.932 --> 00:33:22.390
PROFESSOR: We can
actually relate--

00:33:22.390 --> 00:33:23.848
so we can relate
the binding energy

00:33:23.848 --> 00:33:27.130
to the mass and the mass
parabola analytically,

00:33:27.130 --> 00:33:35.080
because the binding energy is
equal to Z times protons plus N

00:33:35.080 --> 00:33:40.420
times mass of neutron
minus the actual mass

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:45.920
of that same nucleus, A comma
Z. So they're actually directly

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:48.740
related, just negatively.

00:33:48.740 --> 00:33:50.720
So something with
a higher mass is

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:53.300
going to have a low binding
energy, which means it's

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:56.030
less bound and less stable.

00:33:56.030 --> 00:34:00.180
And indeed, the further
up the mass scale we go,

00:34:00.180 --> 00:34:02.690
the higher those
beta or electron

00:34:02.690 --> 00:34:04.757
