00:49:25.990 --> 00:49:28.126
that we say that there's
an island of stability

00:49:28.126 --> 00:49:33.637
because the mass increases
up to the point of unknown?

00:49:33.637 --> 00:49:34.720
PROFESSOR: There's a few--

00:49:34.720 --> 00:49:36.883
so the question was,
is the only reason

00:49:36.883 --> 00:49:39.550
people think there will be super
heavy elements because the mass

00:49:39.550 --> 00:49:40.360
increases, right?

00:49:40.360 --> 00:49:41.260
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:49:41.260 --> 00:49:44.350
PROFESSOR: So in this case,
the mass will always--

00:49:44.350 --> 00:49:47.150
are you talking about
now the total mass or--

00:49:47.150 --> 00:49:49.696
AUDIENCE: Why is
the idea that there

00:49:49.696 --> 00:49:51.317
is this island of stability?

00:49:51.317 --> 00:49:52.520
PROFESSOR: Ah, OK.

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:53.978
AUDIENCE: If this
doesn't prove it,

00:49:53.978 --> 00:49:57.250
do we have other
reasons [INAUDIBLE]??

00:49:57.250 --> 00:49:59.260
PROFESSOR: We have a
few things to go on.

00:49:59.260 --> 00:50:03.520
There are a number of different
aspects of nuclear stability

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:06.010
that are all pointing
to the same conclusion.

00:50:06.010 --> 00:50:08.140
One of them, you can
see on this graph here.

00:50:08.140 --> 00:50:10.180
If you look at the
alpha decay half-life

00:50:10.180 --> 00:50:12.070
as a function of
neutron number, it

00:50:12.070 --> 00:50:15.400
doesn't just increase or
decrease monotonically.

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:17.470
It swells up and down.

00:50:17.470 --> 00:50:20.770
And it reaches a
relative maximum

00:50:20.770 --> 00:50:22.690
near certain magic numbers.

00:50:22.690 --> 00:50:26.110
We can confirm that with
the lower mass nuclei.

00:50:26.110 --> 00:50:27.640
It doesn't work for
really low mass,

00:50:27.640 --> 00:50:31.210
because tiny things don't
tend to undergo alpha decay.

00:50:31.210 --> 00:50:33.760
But there are patterns
that we're simply

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:37.930
recognizing and saying, well, if
this is the next magic number,

00:50:37.930 --> 00:50:39.590
it should continue to increase.

00:50:39.590 --> 00:50:43.600
And I should mention too,
this scale is logarithmic.

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:46.900
So the top right here is
like 10 to the 4 seconds.

00:50:46.900 --> 00:50:49.930
Just so you know, there
are 86,400 seconds

00:50:49.930 --> 00:50:52.060
in-- what is it-- a day.

00:50:52.060 --> 00:50:55.340
And 3 times 10 to the
7 seconds in a year.

00:50:55.340 --> 00:50:56.430
So if this graph--

00:50:56.430 --> 00:50:59.370
let's say for Z 111--

00:50:59.370 --> 00:51:02.280
were to continue
on its track, it

00:51:02.280 --> 00:51:04.500
should reach like
10 to the 9 or 10

00:51:04.500 --> 00:51:08.160
to the 10, which could be
like 100-year lifetimes

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:10.920
or 100-year half-lives,
which means definitely you

00:51:10.920 --> 00:51:13.470
can chemically separate them
and do things with them.

00:51:13.470 --> 00:51:16.350
I don't know if they would
be safe enough to deal with.

00:51:16.350 --> 00:51:18.790
But we also don't really
know what's going to happen.

00:51:18.790 --> 00:51:21.450
You can see that there
is some uncertainty,

00:51:21.450 --> 00:51:23.460
and things don't always
follow the trend.

00:51:23.460 --> 00:51:26.580
Even the error bars are
outside the dashed lines.

00:51:26.580 --> 00:51:27.810
But so we have this to go on.

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:31.260
We have the alpha
decay half-life.

00:51:31.260 --> 00:51:33.630
We also have the
alpha decay energy.

00:51:33.630 --> 00:51:35.790
As you approach an
island of stability,

00:51:35.790 --> 00:51:37.860
something that's more
stable won't give off

00:51:37.860 --> 00:51:40.830
as much kinetic energy
to its alpha particle.

00:51:40.830 --> 00:51:44.520
There is also-- for the
ones that you can actually

00:51:44.520 --> 00:51:46.320
measure that live
long enough, you

00:51:46.320 --> 00:51:48.570
can measure their
mass to charge ratio

00:51:48.570 --> 00:51:51.990
and actually get a good
picture of their actual mass.

00:51:51.990 --> 00:51:55.290
So we would expect
the mass defect

00:51:55.290 --> 00:51:58.650
to follow a certain
trend as we go up.

00:51:58.650 --> 00:52:00.240
The mass is always
going to increase.

00:52:00.240 --> 00:52:03.600
If you add more nucleons,
it's going to increase.

00:52:03.600 --> 00:52:07.800
But the mass defect,
which is the real mass

00:52:07.800 --> 00:52:10.920
minus the atomic number mass--

00:52:10.920 --> 00:52:12.690
if stability were
to increase, do you

00:52:12.690 --> 00:52:15.730
think the mass defect
would increase or decrease

00:52:15.730 --> 00:52:17.404
with more stability?

00:52:22.290 --> 00:52:23.850
Let's take a quick look at this.

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:29.730
If A were to stay the same,
a shrinking real mass--

00:52:29.730 --> 00:52:32.550
and remember, lower mass
means more stability--

00:52:32.550 --> 00:52:38.050
would mean a higher
or a low mass defect?

00:52:38.050 --> 00:52:42.520
It would mean a lower mass
defect or a lower excess mass

00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:43.880
as you'd call it.

00:52:43.880 --> 00:52:48.070
So in this case, you would
expect the mass of the nucleus

00:52:48.070 --> 00:52:53.960
to be smaller than its A if
it was going more stable.

00:52:53.960 --> 00:52:57.060
And all of these trends
work in the same direction,

00:52:57.060 --> 00:53:00.230
which is saying, OK, so
we have the alpha energy.

00:53:00.230 --> 00:53:01.610
We have the mass defect.

00:53:01.610 --> 00:53:04.580
We have the half-life all
pointing to the same thing

00:53:04.580 --> 00:53:07.250
that something should
be more stable.

00:53:07.250 --> 00:53:09.050
And we have some
patterns to go on,

00:53:09.050 --> 00:53:12.470
but our understanding
is kind of incomplete.

00:53:12.470 --> 00:53:14.700
So-- yeah?

00:53:14.700 --> 00:53:18.220
AUDIENCE: So if there's
super heavy elements,

00:53:18.220 --> 00:53:19.810
do they exist
somewhere in space,

00:53:19.810 --> 00:53:21.365
or do stars make them, possibly?

00:53:21.365 --> 00:53:21.990
PROFESSOR: Ooh.

00:53:21.990 --> 00:53:22.960
AUDIENCE: Or are they--

00:53:22.960 --> 00:53:24.756
PROFESSOR: Good question.

00:53:24.756 --> 00:53:26.798
AUDIENCE: --currently made?

00:53:26.798 --> 00:53:29.340
PROFESSOR: So the question is,
if super heavy elements exist,

00:53:29.340 --> 00:53:31.410
do they exist out
there in space?

00:53:31.410 --> 00:53:34.560
I think there would be a
couple places they would exist.

00:53:34.560 --> 00:53:37.950
The source of most of
the elements beyond iron

00:53:37.950 --> 00:53:42.660
is supernovas, where regular old
fusion doesn't cut it anymore.

00:53:42.660 --> 00:53:47.700
When you hit the maximum of
this binding energy per nucleon

00:53:47.700 --> 00:53:50.370
curve, you're at about iron 56.

00:53:50.370 --> 00:53:52.530
That's why stars tend
to form a core of iron

00:53:52.530 --> 00:53:55.560
before it goes really
bad in whatever way it

00:53:55.560 --> 00:53:56.610
does for a star.

00:53:56.610 --> 00:53:58.440
There are multiple ways.

00:53:58.440 --> 00:54:01.980
When you get a supernova,
you have an insane explosion,

00:54:01.980 --> 00:54:03.600
and the core gets
compressed from

00:54:03.600 --> 00:54:08.130
the outside, forcing fusion
of heavy elements to happen.

00:54:08.130 --> 00:54:10.720
That's because you're putting
in extra kinetic energy.

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:14.970
So it's like you have an
endothermic reaction where

00:54:14.970 --> 00:54:19.020
if Q is less than zero, how do
you make that reaction happen?

00:54:19.020 --> 00:54:21.240
Add kinetic energy,
which can come

00:54:21.240 --> 00:54:24.690
from a tremendous explosion
outside of the outer regions

00:54:24.690 --> 00:54:26.128
of the star.

00:54:26.128 --> 00:54:28.420
So who's to say that some of
these super heavy elements

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:30.010
aren't formed in supernovas?

00:54:30.010 --> 00:54:31.820
I think they would be.

00:54:31.820 --> 00:54:35.163
But would they actually make
it out to be part of Earth

00:54:35.163 --> 00:54:37.580
and then, let's say, live the
5 billion years that Earth's

00:54:37.580 --> 00:54:38.510
been around?

00:54:38.510 --> 00:54:41.290
We don't know if their
half-lives are long enough.

00:54:41.290 --> 00:54:44.940
There very well may have
been some 5 billion years ago

00:54:44.940 --> 00:54:46.880
or when the supernova was made.

00:54:46.880 --> 00:54:49.490
But we haven't detected
any here on Earth.

00:54:49.490 --> 00:54:53.760
So we know that they're
not 5 billion years stable.

00:54:53.760 --> 00:54:56.140
Rather, I wouldn't
even say we know that,

00:54:56.140 --> 00:54:58.790
but we have a pretty good idea.

00:54:58.790 --> 00:55:01.932
That's a great question is
like, are they naturally made?

00:55:01.932 --> 00:55:04.412
Probably.

00:55:04.412 --> 00:55:06.400
Yeah.

00:55:06.400 --> 00:55:08.020
Any other questions?

00:55:08.020 --> 00:55:09.940
I like these outside
the material ones.

00:55:09.940 --> 00:55:13.810
We can take things beyond
our known universe,

00:55:13.810 --> 00:55:15.960
start to explain them.